
Variable names in POSIX shell consist of underscores, ASCII letters,
and digits, with the constraint that the first character cannot be
a digit. [A-Za-z_][A-Za-z_0-9]*.

Function names should follow the same rule, but Bash is permissive.
In practice, bash accepts any word that isn't a reserved word and
doesn't contain shell metacharacters (|, &, ;, (, ), <, >, space,
tab, newline). (so ':', '-', and '.' all work in function names.)
